{
  "doc_id": "40107",
  "text": "In a recent series of papers examining visual working memory, Palva and colleagues have demonstrated how synchrony can support memory [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In their studies, they mapped the dynamics of network synchrony during the performance of a memory task and found that there was sustained phase synchrony in parietal/frontal circuits in three frequency bands. Perhaps most important was the finding that the synchrony increased as a function of the memory load. They suggested that the synchrony among the various brain regions could reflect a compensatory mechanism to help deal with retention of information, when that information load rises above working memory \"capacity\" (usually in the range of 3-4 items). This is a provocative finding in the present context because the data suggests that there is some form of compensatory response possible in the early stages of MCI and AD [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
